# The for loop written here converts all the object Dtypes into categorical types
for feature in bankdata_df.columns:
  if bankdata_df[feature].dtype == 'object':
    bankdata_df[feature] = pd.Categorical(bankdata_df[feature])

                  "education":{"primary":1,"secondary":2,"tertiary":3,"unknown":-1},

In [21]:
# this prints out the heatmap of the correlations for each of the column to help in bivariate analysis
# From the heatmap we can see pdays, previous and poutcome have high correlation with each other.
# But the highest positive impact on the target variable 'Target' seems to be 'duration'. 
# Even then this is plays a very mild impact on 'Target'. So we can conclude from this that only 
# a few group of variables have strong correlations with each other but towards target there are no influence from the other variable except 'duration'.
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
sns.heatmap(bankeval_df.corr(),annot=True,linewidths=.5,center=0,cbar=True,cmap="YlGnBu",vmin=-1,vmax=+1)
plt.show()

# AOC FOR LOGISTIC REGRESSION

from sklearn.multiclass import OneVsRestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve,auc
clf = OneVsRestClassifier(LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear"))
y_score = clf.fit(X_train, y_train).predict_proba(X_test)

fpr = dict()
tpr = dict()
roc_auc = dict()
for i in range(n_classes):
    fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_test_bin[:, i], y_score[:, i])
    roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])
colors = ['blue', 'red', 'green']
for i, color in zip(range(n_classes), colors):
    plt.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], color=color, lw=2,
             label='ROC curve of class {0} (area = {1:0.2f})'
             ''.format(i, roc_auc[i]))

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', lw=2)
plt.xlim([-0.05, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic for multi-class data')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()
